orth and South. Years after the war she published an anonymous essay still bristling at the Union's victory."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"She fought to keep her own land","body":"When her father's bankruptcy swept the Looking Glass plantation into his creditors' hands, Edmondston battled through the state supreme court to hold it. Less than a month before her death she won it back with the highest bid at its forced sale."},{"category":"education","header":"Her father schooled his daughters like sons","body":"Thomas Pollock Devereux had his daughters tutored in literature, mathematics, science, and philosophy, an education matching what his son received at Yale. Catherine finished at Belmont, a girls' school near Leesburg, Virginia.","number":4},{"category":"legacy","header":"Her diary outlived the world it defended","body":"Childless and bitter in defeat, Edmondston left no heirs but a journal historians now mine for its unsparing view of the Confederate home front. Published in 1979, it remains one of the fullest such records from North Carolina.","number":5}],"slug":"catherine-devereux-1823"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}